name: ARPANET
description:
- Advanced Research Projects Agency Network
- the first wide-area packet-switched network with distributed control and one of the first computer networks to implement the TCP/IP protocol suite. Both technologies became the technical foundation of the Internet.
- Initiated in 1966, first computers connected in 1969

name: Netscape Navigator
description:
- Developed by people who had developed Mosaic browser for NCSA in 1993. They had started company called Mosaic Communications Corporation in April 1994, and in october of the same year they released Mosaic Netscape 0.9 which was soon renamed to Netscape Navigator. The company was also renamed to Netscape.
- Internally referred to as Mozilla, meaning the Mosaic killer

name: JavaScript
description: - developed by Brendan Eich at Netscape

name: Java
description: - Java language project was initiated in 1991

name: First rocks
description: Earth's surface had apparently been molten until then.

name: The oldest undisputed evidence of life on Earth
description: Interpreted as fossilized bacteria, dates to 3 Ga. Other finds in rocks dated to about 3.5 Ga have been interpreted as bacteria, with geochemical evidence also seeming to show the presence of life 3.8 Ga. However, these analyses were closely scrutinized, and non-biological processes were found which could produce all of the "signatures of life" that had been reported.

name: Oldest evidence for microbial life
description: In the form of organic matter-rich paleosols, ephemeral ponds and alluvial sequences, some bearing microfossils

name: The first disputed evidence of life on Earth
description: Biologically fractionated graphite inside a single zircon grain in the Jack Hills range of Australia.

name: Homo sapiens
description:
Anatomically modern human.

The earliest fossil evidence of early modern humans appears in Africa around 300,000 years ago, with the earliest genetic splits among modern people, according to some evidence, dating to around the same time.

name: Chimpanzee–human last common ancestor
description: Seems to be quite unclear still. Studies in the early 2020s suggest a more recent CHLCA, such as between 9.3 and 6.5 million years ago in 2021, and studies giving even more recent dates are cited in a 2022 article.

name: Writing
description:
Four independent inventions of writing are most commonly recognized:
- Mesopotamia (c. 3400–3100 BC)
- Egypt (c. 3250 BC)
- China (before c. 1250 BC)
- Mesoamerica (before c. 1 AD)

name: Great Pyramid of Giza
description:
- Original height: 146.6 m
- The tallest pyramid in the world

name: Sargon of Akkad
description: A face mask (probably) depicting Sargon made sometime during the Akkadian period. Most likely representing either Sargon of Akkad or his grandson Naram-Sin.

name: Priest-King statue of Indus valley
description: The most famous statue of the Indus valley civilization.

name: Statue of a copulating couple from Babylonia
Harp player statue from Greek islands
Stag statuette
description: Alaca, Anatolia. Bronze (with silver inlay). Symbol of a Hittite male god.

name: Mask of “Agamemnon”
description: Discovered at the Bronze Age site of Mycenae in southern Greece.

name: Ziggurat of Dur Kurigalzu
description: Founded by Kassite king of Babylon, Kurigalzu I

name: Mask of Tutankhamun
description: His grave was perhaps safe from robbers because he died fairly young (19) and was thus largely forgotten.

name: Merneptah stele
description: The earliest mention of Israel in any writing.

name: Olmec colossal heads
description: Olmec were an early known major Mesoamerican civilization, flourishing in the modern-day Mexican states of Veracruz and Tabasco from roughly 1200 to 400 BCE during Mesoamerica's formative period

name: Crocodilia
description: The earliest stage of crocodilian evolution was the protosuchians in the late Triassic and early Jurassic.

name: Caniform and Feliform split
description: Around 50 million years ago, or earlier, in the Paleocene, the Carnivora split into two main divisions: caniform (dog-like) and feliform (cat-like).

name: Bird
description: Key features of Archaeopteryx that link it to birds include feathers and the ability to potentially glide or fly. However, it also had characteristics typical of theropod dinosaurs, such as teeth, a long bony tail, and claws on its wings. This mixture of traits made Archaeopteryx a crucial fossil in understanding the evolution of birds from theropod dinosaurs.

name: Domestication of Goat, Sheep, Pig, Cow
Domestication of Chicken
description: Apparently for cockfighting rather than for food.

name: Last Glacial Period ended
description:
Started 115,000 years ago.

The last Glacial Maximum occurred 20,000 years ago.

name: Agricultural revolution
description: The prehistoric transition from hunting and gathering to settled agriculture (also known as the Neolithic Revolution).

name: Hand axe
description: A prehistoric stone tool with two faces.

name: Homo erectus
description: Walking upright. Spread from Africa to Eurasia.

name: Use of fire on daily basis
Fictive language
description: Homo Sapiens spread to Arabian Peninsula and quickly to rest of the Eurasia.

name: Multicellular organism
description: The Francevillian biota (Also referred to as Gabon macrofossils, Gabonionta or Francevillian group fossils) are a collection of 2.1-billion-year-old Palaeoproterozoic macroscopic structures, controversially suggested to be fossils. The structures have been postulated by some authors to be evidence of the earliest form of multicellular life, and of eukaryotes

name: Fungus
description:
The oldest fossilizied mycelium to be identified from its molecular composition is between 715 and 810 million years old.

The earliest fossils possessing features typical of fungi date to the Paleoproterozoic era, some 2,400 million years ago (Ma); these multicellular benthic organisms had filamentous structures capable of anastomosis.[121] Other studies (2009) estimate the arrival of fungal organisms at about 760–1060 Ma on the basis of comparisons of the rate of evolution in closely related groups.

name: The last snowball earth
description:
The most academically mentioned period of such a global ice age is believed to have occurred some time before 650 mya during the Cryogenian period, which included at least two large glacial periods, the Sturtian and Marinoan glaciations.

The first Snowball Earth event is believed to have occurred during the Sturtian glaciation, around 720 to 700 million years ago.

Some propose there was a snowball earth already around 2300 B years ago when the atmosphere started to get oxygen-rich.

name: Milky Way
description:
The thin disk of our galaxy began to form when the universe was about 5 billion years old or 9 ± 2 Gya.

According to recent studies, the Milky Way as well as the Andromeda Galaxy lie in what in the galaxy color–magnitude diagram is known as the "green valley", a region populated by galaxies in transition from the "blue cloud" (galaxies actively forming new stars) to the "red sequence" (galaxies that lack star formation).

name: Andromeda
description: The Andromeda Galaxy (M31) is estimated to be around 10 billion years old, though some of its oldest stars and globular clusters may be as old as 13.5 billion years, similar to the Milky Way. Andromeda formed through multiple galaxy mergers over billions of years, which shaped it into the massive spiral galaxy we see today.

name: Woolly mammoth
description: The youngest fossils of the mainland population are from the Kyttyk Peninsula of Siberia and date to 9,650 years ago

name: Sabre-tooth tiger
description: Smilodon. Although commonly known as the saber-toothed tiger, it was not closely related to the tiger or other modern cats.

name: Sumer
description:
Most historians have suggested that Sumer was first permanently settled between c. 5500 and c. 3300 BC.

Abandoned 1800 BC

name: Assur
description: Archaeology reveals the site of the city was occupied by the middle of the 3rd millennium BC.

name: Memphis
description: During the Early Dynastic Period (3150 BC - 2686 BC) and Old Kingdom, Memphis became the capital of Ancient Egypt for more than six consecutive dynasties.

name: Athens
description: Athens has been continuously inhabited for at least 5,000 years. By 1400 BC, the settlement had become an important centre of the Mycenaean civilization

name: Kish
description: Kish was occupied from the Ubaid period (5300-4300 BC). The Sumerian King List (2084-1648 BC) states that Kish was the first city to have kings following the deluge.

name: Sumerian King List
description:
Redacted to legitimize the claims to power of various city-states and kingdoms in southern Mesopotamia during the late third and early second millennium BC.

Publication date (2084-1648 BC).

name: Charlemagne
description: Born 748. Died 814. Holy Roman Emperor in 800.

name: Constantine the Great
description: Born 272. Died 337. Contested Roman Emperor since 306. Undisputed since 324.

name: Christopher Colmubus
description:
Born 1451. Died 1506.

The posthumous portrait of a man, said to be Christopher Columbus, was painted by Sebastiano del Piombo in 1519.

name: Troy II
description: Twice the size of the preceding city.

name: Troy VI
description:
Destroyed around 1300 BC. Indicative of an earthquake.

Troy VI–VII is believed to be the city referred to as Wilusa and Taruisa in Hittite records

name: Mycenae
description: The dominant state in Greece during the Late Helladic period (1550-1050 BC).

name: Pyramid of Djoser
description:
- 2670 - 2650 BC
- The first pyramid
- Height: 62.5 m

name: Toniná pyramid
description:
- height: 74 m
- The tallest pyramid in America

name: La Venta pyramid
description:
- height: 34 m
- The oldest pyramid in America

name: Inanna seal
description:
2350–2150 BC

Originally worshipped in Sumer, she was known by the Akkadian Empire, Babylonians, and Assyrians as Ishtar. Her primary title is "the Queen of Heaven".

name: Bronze head
description: This bronze head traditionally attributed to Sargon is now thought to actually belong to his grandson Naram-Sin.

name: Hittite vase with a bull-leaping scene
Relief of Tiglath-Pileser III
description:
- 745 - 727 BC 
- Under Tiglath-Pileser the Neo-Assyrian Empire was consolidated, centralized and significantly expanded

name: Lachish reliefs
description:
- Carved between 700 - 681 BC 
- Narrates the story of the Assyrian victory over the kingdom of Judah during the siege of Lachish in 701 BC

name: Colosseum
description: Construction began under the Emperor Vespasian (r. 69–79 AD) in 72 and was completed in AD 80 under his successor and heir, Titus (r. 79–81).

name: Al-Khazneh, Petra
description: Petra flourished in the 1st century AD, when its Al-Khazneh structure, possibly the mausoleum of Nabataean king Aretas IV, was constructed, and its population peaked at an estimated 20,000 inhabitants. Nabataea fell to the Romans in 106, who annexed and renamed it Arabia Petraea.

name: Alhambra
description: The complex was begun in 1238. The most significant construction campaigns, which gave the royal palaces much of their defining character, took place in the 14th century.

name: The Virgin and Child with Saints Francis and Sebastian
Sandro Botticelli
description:
Born 1445. Died 1510.

The posthumous portrait of a man, said to be Christopher Columbus, was painted by Sebastiano del Piombo in 1519.

name: Ascension of Christ and Noli me tangere
description: See Drogo Sacramentary for a similar Ascension 450 years later.

name: Diptych of Anicius Petronius Probus
description: The diptych is depicting emperor Honorus. It's a gift from Anicius Petronius Probus, consul in 406, to his supporters. This distribution of commemorative diptychs to supporters was a very common tradition in those times.

name: Diptych of Justin
description: Flavius Mar. Petrus Theodorus Valentinus Rusticius Boraides Germanus Iustinus, simply and commonly known as Justin, was consul in 540.

name: Drogo Sacramentary
description: A Carolingian illuminated manuscript on vellum

name: Coptic icon of Jesus and an abbot
Stora Hammars stones
description: The Stora Hammars image stones are four Viking Age image stones located in Stora Hammars, Lärbro parish, Gotland, Sweden.

name: Votive crown
description: Votive crown of the Visigoth King Recceswinth, made of gold and precious stones in the 2nd half of the 7th century. Part of the Treasure of Guarrazar.

name: Codex Aureus of Lorsch
description: The Codex Aureus of Lorsch or Lorsch Gospels is an illuminated Gospel Book written in Latin between 778 and 820.

name: The adoration of the Lamb
description: From the Codex Aureus of Saint Emmeram

name: Charles the Bald
description: From the Codex Aureus of Saint Emmeram

name: Virgin and Child with John the Baptist and Zachary's
description: From the Codex Aureus of Lorsch.

name: Evangelist portrait
description: From the Codex Aureus of Lorsch.

name: Icon of Mary
description: The oldest Byzantine icon of Mary, c. 600, encaustic, at Saint Catherine's Monastery retains much of Greek realist style.

name: Mary Magdalene announces the Risen Christ
description: From the St. Albans Psalter, an English Illuminated manuscript. Created at or for St. Albans Abbey in the 12th century.

name: Historiated initial
description: French historiated initial with men slaying a monster, from a theological manuscript. 1110–1115.

name: Married slaves in a relief
description: Funerary relief (ca. 80 BC) celebrating the marriage between Aurelius Hermia and Aurelia Philematium as conliberti, fellow slaves in the same household who were freed.

name: Manumission ceremony
description: Fragment of a marble relief (1st century BC) depicting a manumission ceremony and the wearing of the pileus, a felt cap that was a symbol of liberation.

name: Captives in chains
description: Relief from Smyrna (present-day İzmir, Turkey) depicting a Roman soldier leading captives in chains

name: Funerary bust of a slave child
description: By the common law of nations (ius gentium), the child of a legally enslaved mother was born a slave. The Latin word for a slave born within the familia of a household (domus) or agricultural estate (villa) was verna, plural vernae.

name: The Roman Empire at its greatest extent
A slave-trader
description: Funerary monument of Gaius Aiacius, a slave-trader (mango).

name: Horse-powered millstone
description: Horse-powered millstone. Marble, panel of a Roman sarcophagus, 3rd century CE. From the Vigna Tre Madonne, oustide the Porta San Giovanni in Rome

name: Gravesite marker
description: Gravesite marker (2nd century AD) for the wool merchant Titus Aelius Evangelus, likely a freedman of Antoninus Pius.

name: Inscription honoring an imperial freedman
description: Inscription from the base of a statue honoring the imperial freedman Publius Aelius Liberalis as the patron of the vicus Augustanus in Ostia, where he held several governmental positions up to that of procurator of the grain supply.

name: Scene from Roman comedy
description: Terra cotta relief (late 1st century BC–early 1st century AD): a slave seeks refuge at an altar to escape his master's punishment in a scene from Roman comedy.

name: Slaves of love
description: Mosaic (early 4th century) depicting two fishermen Cupids at left wearing servile clothing, with a V for Venus forehead tattoo chastising them as penal slaves of love.

name: Crucifixion of Jesus
description: One of the earliest extant depictions (ca. AD 420–430) of the crucifixion of Jesus, on an ivory carving that also shows the suicide of Judas: the crucified Christ is serenely detached from the suffering of torture[739] and defiantly alive on a dead tree, while Judas hangs dead on a living tree.

name: Defeated Dacian king
description: A relief from Trajan's Column shows the defeated Dacian king Decebalus surrounded by Roman cavalry and holding his sica to his throat, in the moment before he commits suicide to escape captivity (from the plates of Conrad Cichorius).

name: Slave collar with a tag
description: Obtained slave iron collar with a bronze plate from the 4th to 5th century. The engraved inscription commends a reward from a gold coin that leads the escaped wearer back to his owner Zoninus.

name: A foetus in the womb
description: A page showing Leonardo da Vinci's study of a foetus in the womb.

name: A scythed chariot and a fighting vehicle
description:
- Leonardo da Vinci
- Drawings of a scythed chariot and a fighting vehicle

name: Judith Beheading Holofernes
description:
- Caravaggio
- Judith Beheading Holofernes, 1599–1602, Galleria Nazionale d'Arte Antica, Rome

name: The Burial of the Count of Orgaz
description:
- El Greco
- The Burial of the Count of Orgaz (1586–1588, oil on canvas, 480 × 360 cm, church of Santo Tomé, Toledo), now El Greco's best known work, illustrates a popular local legend. An exceptionally large painting, it is clearly divided into two zones: the heavenly above and the terrestrial below, brought together compositionally.

name: View of Toledo
description:
- El Greco
- View of Toledo (c. 1596–1600, oil on canvas, 47.75 × 42.75 cm, Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York) is one of the two surviving landscapes of Toledo painted by El Greco.

name: Self-portrait at 26
description:
- Albrecht Dürer
- the second of Albrecht Dürer's three painted self-portraits and was executed in oil on wood panel in 1498, after his first trip to Italy

name: Handling of Weapons
description:
- Albrecht Dürer
- Page from the Meditation on the Handling of Weapons

name: The Boulevard du Temple
description: A daguerreotype made by Louis Daguerre in 1838, is generally accepted as the earliest photograph to include people.

name: Portrait photo
description: Albert Bierstadt photographed by his brother Edward Bierstadt. May be the oldest surviving color portrait photograph.

name: Portrait photo
description: Alim Khan photographed by Sergey Prokudin-Gorsky using Maxwell's method.

name: Savery Steam Pump
description: The first commercially successful steam powered device, built by Thomas Savery.

name: Flying shuttle
description: Weavers could operate faster, and large cloths could be made by a single weaver.

name: Newcomen steam engine
description: Historically significant as the first practical device to harness steam to produce mechanical work.

name: Pocahontas
description:
- Engraving by Simon de Passe
- Pocahontas lived 1596 - 1617
- Pocahontas was presented to English society as an example of the "civilized savage" in hopes of stimulating investment in Jamestown

name: Iron bridge
description: The first major bridge in the world to be made of cast iron.

name: Watt steam engine
description: A critical improvement to newcomen steam engine.

name: Cotton gin
description: A machine that quickly and easily separates cotton fibers from their seeds, enabling much greater productivity than manual cotton separation.

name: Roberts Loom
description: The first loom that was more viable than a hand loom.

name: Colt revolver
description: Samuel Colt patented a popular revolver which led to the widespread use of the revolver.

name: Morse system
description: The Morse system for telegraphy, which was first used in about 1844, was designed to make indentations on a paper tape when electric currents were received

name: Corliss steam engine
description: Engines fitted with Corliss valve gear offered the best thermal efficiency of any type of stationary steam engine until the refinement of the uniflow steam engine and steam turbine in the 20th century.

name: Wooden rails
description: Wagonways (or tramways), with wooden rails and horse-drawn traffic, are known to have been used in the 1550s to facilitate transportation of ore tubs to and from mines. They soon became popular in Europe and an example of their operation was illustrated by Georgius Agricola (see image) in his 1556 work De re metallica.

name: Salamanca locomotive
description: The first commercially successful steam locomotive.

name: Paixhans gun
description: The first naval gun designed to fire explosive shells

name: Battle tank
description: The first offensive using tanks took place on 15 September 1916, during the Battle of the Somme. Forty-nine of the Mark I type were committed, of which thirty-two were mechanically fit to take part in the advance and achieved some small, local successes.

name: Flight
description: The Wright Flyer made the first sustained flight by a manned heavier-than-air powered and controlled aircraft on December 17, 1903.

name: Ford Model T
description: The first mass-affordable automobile, which made car travel available to middle-class Americans.

name: Hot-air balloon flight
description: The first manned hot-air balloon, designed by the Montgolfier brothers, takes off from the Bois de Boulogne, Paris, on November 21, 1783.

name: Hourglass
description: The first documented example dates from the 14th century, a depiction in the 1338 fresco Allegory of Good Government by Ambrogio Lorenzetti.

name: Compass
description: The first recorded appearance of the use of the compass in Europe, as a description of a magnetized needle and its use among sailors, occurs in Alexander Neckam's De naturis rerum (On the Natures of Things), written in 1190.

name: Coca-Cola
description: The picture is from 1888, and is believed to be the first coupon.

name: Billy the Kid
description:
- 1859 - 1881
- Portrait attributed to Ben Wittick, c. 1880

name: Chocolate in Europe
description: The earliest documented introduction to the Spanish court occurred in 1544, but it was not until 1585 that the first official shipment of cacao to Europe was recorded. In the 18th century, chocolate was considered southern European, aristocratic and Catholic. This was in contrast to the bourgeois coffee and proletarian alcohol.

name: Pacification of Ghent
description: An alliance between the provinces of the Habsburg Netherlands gets rid of the plundering mercenaries, that the bankrupt Spain couldn't pay for.

name: Potato in Europe
description: The first written mention of the potato is a receipt for delivery dated 28 November 1567 between Las Palmas in the Grand Canaries and Antwerp.

name: Compromise of Nobles
description: A covenant of members of the nobility in the Habsburg Netherlands who came together to submit a petition to the Regent Margaret of Parma on 5 April 1566, with the objective of obtaining a moderation of the placards against heresy in the Netherlands. This petition played a crucial role in the events leading up to the Dutch Revolt and the Eighty Years' War.

name: Treaty of Arras
description: Southern parts of the Netherlands (Union of Arras) sign a separate peace treaty with the Spanish Crown. The northern Union of Utrecht continues the war.

name: Sack of Antwerp
description: Plundering mercenaries sack Antwerp after not getting paid by the bankrupt Spain.

name: Peace of Augsburg
description: A treaty between Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor, and the Schmalkaldic League. Allowed rulers to choose either Lutheranism or Roman Catholicism as the official confession of their state.

name: Tobacco in Europe
description: Diego Columbus mentioned a tobacco merchant of Lisbon in his will.

name: Coffee in Europe
description: Coffee was first introduced to Europe in Hungary when the Turks invaded Hungary at the Battle of Mohács in 1526.

name: German Peasants' War
description: Europe's largest and most widespread popular uprising before the French Revolution of 1789.

name: Circumnavigation
description: Magellan Expedition returns to Spain without Magellan.

name: Field of the Cloth of Gold
description: Summit arranged to increase the bond of friendship between France and England following the Anglo-French treaty of 1514.

name: Concordat of Bologna
description: Permitted the Pope to collect all the income that the Catholic Church made in France, while the King of France was confirmed in his right to tithe the clerics and to restrict their right of appeal to Rome. Superseded the Pragmatic Sanction of Bourges (1438).

name: Hussite Wars
description: A series of civil wars fought between the Hussites and the combined Catholic forces of Holy Roman Emperor Sigismund, the Papacy, and European monarchs loyal to the Catholic Church.

name: Holyday
description: Thought to originally have been part of a diptych depicting Tissot's garden in St. John's, alongside A Convalescent.

name: Elizabeth Linley
description: Elizabeth Linley, Mrs Richard Brinsley Sheridan (1754-1792) as Saint Cecilia. The famous singer is shown as the patron saint of music.

name: The Ladies Waldegrave

Before that, it was proposed in the 1960s to have depicted Olaudah Equiano and to have been painted by Joshua Reynolds c. 1780 with the title Portrait of a Negro Man.

name: David Garrick
description: David Garrick (19 February 1716 – 20 January 1779) was an English actor, playwright, theatre manager and producer who influenced nearly all aspects of European theatrical practice throughout the 18th century, and was a pupil and friend of Samuel Johnson.

description: Paul Legrand, born Charles-Dominique-Martin Legrand, was a highly regarded and influential French mime who turned the Pierrot of his predecessor, Jean-Gaspard Deburau, into the tearful, sentimental character that is most familiar to post-19th-century admirers of the figure.

name: Lisztomania
description:
First occurred in Berlin in 1841 and the term was later coined by Heinrich Heine in a feuilleton he wrote on 25 April 1844, discussing the 1844 Parisian concert season. Lisztomania was characterized by intense levels of hysteria demonstrated by fans, akin to the treatment of some celebrity musicians starting in the second half of the 20th century – but in a time not known for such musical excitement.

The caricature is from 1842 by Theodor Hosemann.
